docs.abstract: Thomas Lane, 39, helped to hold Mr. Floyd down while another officer fatally knelt on his neck. He was the only officer to suggest they should roll Mr. Floyd on his side so he could breathe.
docs.snippet: Thomas Lane, 39, helped to hold Mr. Floyd down while another officer fatally knelt on his neck. He was the only officer to suggest they should roll Mr. Floyd on his side so he could breathe.
docs.lead_paragraph: ST. PAUL, Minn. — Thomas Lane, a former Minneapolis police officer who held down George Floyd’s legs as he gasped for air while dying under the knee of another officer, was sentenced to two and a half years in prison on Thursday.

headline.main: Ex-Officer Who Held George Floyd’s Legs Sentenced to 30 Months in Prison
headline.print_headline: Ex-Officer Gets 30 Months For Violating Floyd’s Rights

byline.original: By Jeffrey C. Kummer and Nicholas Bogel-Burroughs

docs.lead_paragraph: “Black lives matter because Black wombs matter!” Shawnee Benton Gibson chanted from the stage during a National Action Network rally in Washington, D.C., in 2020.

headline.main: ‘History Is Everything’: Making a Film About Black Maternal Mortality
headline.print_headline: Black Maternal Mortality Moves Into Focus

docs.abstract: A judge sentenced J. Alexander Kueng, who helped hold Mr. Floyd down, to three years in prison, and Tou Thao, who kept bystanders away, to three and a half years.
docs.snippet: A judge sentenced J. Alexander Kueng, who helped hold Mr. Floyd down, to three years in prison, and Tou Thao, who kept bystanders away, to three and a half years.
docs.lead_paragraph: ST. PAUL, Minn. — A former Minneapolis police officer who kept bystanders away from George Floyd and another who helped pin Mr. Floyd down as he struggled to breathe were each sentenced to several years in prison on Wednesday, the last of the four officers involved in Mr. Floyd’s death to be ordered to prison.

headline.main: Last 2 Officers Involved in George Floyd’s Death Are Sentenced to Prison
headline.print_headline: Final Two Officers Sentenced in Floyd’s Death

byline.original: By Jeffrey C. Kummer and Nicholas Bogel-Burroughs

docs.abstract: Derek Chauvin, already serving more than 22 years in state prison for murder, pleaded guilty to federal charges that he used excessive force against Mr. Floyd and a 14-year-old boy.
docs.snippet: Derek Chauvin, already serving more than 22 years in state prison for murder, pleaded guilty to federal charges that he used excessive force against Mr. Floyd and a 14-year-old boy.
docs.lead_paragraph: ST. PAUL, Minn — A white Minneapolis police officer whose murder of a Black man outside a convenience store touched off protests around the world was sentenced to 21 years in federal prison on Thursday, in a case that signaled a new readiness to hold police officers criminally accountable for misconduct.

headline.main: Killer of George Floyd Sentenced to 21 Years for Violating Civil Rights
headline.print_headline: Chauvin Is Sentenced To 21 Years in a Case Of Civil Rights Violations

byline.original: By Jay Senter and Shaila Dewan

docs.abstract: Timothy Loehmann left his position as a police officer in a rural Pennsylvania community just two days after he was sworn in.
docs.snippet: Timothy Loehmann left his position as a police officer in a rural Pennsylvania community just two days after he was sworn in.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two days after Timothy Loehmann, the former Cleveland police officer who shot and killed 12-year-old Tamir Rice in 2014, was sworn in as a police officer for a rural Pennsylvania community, he left the position, the borough of Tioga announced on Thursday.

headline.main: Cleveland Officer Who Killed Tamir Rice Swiftly Exits New Police Job
headline.print_headline: Former Officer Who Shot Child Exits New Job After 2 Days

docs.lead_paragraph: An article on July 22 about the sentencing of a former Minneapolis police officer who held down George Floyd’s legs included an outdated reference to the upcoming state trial of two other officers, J. Alexander Kueng and Tou Thao. It is now scheduled to begin in October, not in January.
